# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ext4-filesystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Stephen Tweedie first revealed that he was working on extending ext2 in *Journaling the Linux ext2fs Filesystem* in a 1998 paper, and later in a February 1999 kernel mailing list posting.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The filesystem was merged with the mainline Linux kernel in November 2001 from 2.4.15 onward.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The speed performance of ext3 is less attractive than competing Linux filesystems, such as ext4, JFS, ReiserFS, and XFS, but ext3 has a significant advantage in that it allows in-place upgrades from ext2 without having to back up and restore data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Benchmarks suggest that ext3 also uses less CPU power than ReiserFS and XFS.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] It is also considered safer than the other Linux file systems, due to its relative simplicity and wider testing base.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Without these features, any ext3 file system is also a valid ext2 file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] This situation has allowed well-tested and mature file system maintenance utilities for maintaining and repairing ext2 file systems to also be used with ext3 without major changes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The ext2 and ext3 file systems share the same standard set of utilities, e2fsprogs, which includes an fsck tool.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The close relationship also makes conversion between the two file systems (both forward to ext3 and backward to ext2) straightforward.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] ext3 lacks "modern" filesystem features, such as dynamic inode allocation and extents.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] This situation might sometimes be a disadvantage, but for recoverability, it is a significant advantage.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The file system metadata is all in fixed, well-known locations, and data structures have some redundancy.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] In significant data corruption, ext2 or ext3 may be recoverable, while a tree-based file system may not.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The maximum number of blocks for ext3 is 232.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Both metadata and file contents are written to the journal before being committed to the main file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Because the journal is relatively continuous on disk, this can improve performance, if the journal has enough space.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] In other cases, performance gets worse, because the data must be written twice—once to the journal, and once to the main part of the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Only metadata is journaled; file contents are not, but it's guaranteed that file contents are written to disk before associated metadata is marked as committed in the journal.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] This is the default on many Linux distributions.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] while a file is being written or appended to, the journal will indicate that the new file or appended data has not been "committed", so it will be purged by the cleanup process.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] can be corrupted because the original version of the file is not stored.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Thus it's possible to end up with a file in an intermediate state between new and old, without enough information to restore either one or the other (the new data never made it to disk completely, and the old data is not stored anywhere).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Even worse, the intermediate state might intersperse old and new data, because the order of the write is left up to the disk's hardware.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Only metadata is journaled; file contents are not.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The contents might be written before or after the journal is updated.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] As a result, files modified right before a crash can become corrupted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] For example, a file being appended to may be marked in the journal as being larger than it actually is, causing garbage at the end.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Older versions of files could also appear unexpectedly after a journal recovery.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The lack of synchronization between data and journal is faster in many cases.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] JFS uses this level of journaling, but ensures that any "garbage" due to unwritten data is zeroed out on reboot.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] In all three modes, the internal structure of file system is assured to be consistent even after a crash.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] In any case, only the data content of files or directories which were being modified when the system crashed will be affected; the rest will be intact after recovery.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Because ext3 aims to be backward-compatible with the earlier ext2, many of the on-disk structures are similar to those of ext2.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Consequently, ext3 lacks recent features, such as extents, dynamic allocation of inodes, and block sub-allocation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] A directory can have at most 31998 *subdirectories*, because an inode can have at most 32,000 links (each direct subdirectory increases their parent folder inode link counter in the ".." reference).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] On ext3, like for most current Linux filesystems, the system tool "fsck" should not be used while the filesystem is mounted for writing.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Attempting to check a filesystem that is already mounted in read/write mode will (very likely) detect inconsistencies in the filesystem metadata.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Where filesystem metadata is changing, and fsck applies changes in an attempt to bring the "inconsistent" metadata into a "consistent" state, the attempt to "fix" the inconsistencies will corrupt the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There is no online ext3 defragmentation tool that works on the filesystem level.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There is an offline ext2 defragmenter, `e2defrag`.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] However, `e2defrag` may destroy data, depending on the feature bits turned on in the filesystem; it does not know how to handle many of the newer ext3 features.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There are userspace defragmentation tools, like Shake and defrag.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Shake works by allocating space for the whole file as one operation, which will generally cause the allocator to find contiguous disk space.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] If there are files which are used at the same time, Shake will try to write them next to one another.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Defrag works by copying each file over itself.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] However, this strategy works only if the file system has enough free space.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] A true defragmentation tool does not exist for ext3.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] However, as the Linux System Administrator Guide states, "Modern Linux filesystem(s) keep fragmentation at a minimum by keeping all blocks in a file close together, even if they can't be stored in consecutive sectors.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Some filesystems, like ext3, effectively allocate the free block that is nearest to other blocks in a file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] While ext3 is resistant to file fragmentation, ext3 can get fragmented over time or for specific usage patterns, like slowly writing large files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Consequently, ext4 (the successor to ext3) has an online filesystem defragmentation utility e4defrag and currently supports extents (contiguous file regions).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] ext3 does not support the recovery of deleted files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The ext3 driver actively deletes files by wiping file inodes for crash safety reasons.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There are still several techniques and some free and proprietary software for recovery of deleted or lost files using file system journal analysis; however, they do not guarantee any specific file recovery.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] e3compr is an unofficial patch for ext3 that does transparent compression.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] It is a direct port of e2compr and still needs further development.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] It compiles and boots well with upstream kernels, but journaling is not implemented yet.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Unlike a number of modern file systems, ext3 does not have native support for snapshots, the ability to quickly capture the state of the filesystem at arbitrary times.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Instead, it relies on less-space-efficient, volume-level snapshots provided by the Linux LVM.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The Next3 file system is a modified version of ext3 which offers snapshots support, yet retains compatibility with the ext3 on-disk format.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] ext3 does not do checksumming when writing to the journal.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] On a storage device with extra cache, if *barrier=1* is not enabled as a mount option (in /etc/fstab), and if the hardware is doing out-of-order write caching, one runs the risk of severe filesystem corruption during a crash.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] This is because storage devices with write caches report to the system that the data has been completely written, even if it was written to the (volatile) cache.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] If hard disk writes are done out-of-order (due to modern hard disks caching writes in order to amortize write speeds), it is likely that one will write a commit block of a transaction before the other relevant blocks are written.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] If a power failure or unrecoverable crash should occur before the other blocks get written, the system will have to be rebooted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Upon reboot, the file system will replay the log as normal, and replay the "winners" (transactions with a commit block, including the invalid transaction above, which happened to be tagged with a valid commit block).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The unfinished disk write above will thus proceed, but using corrupt journal data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The file system will thus mistakenly overwrite normal data with corrupt data while replaying the journal.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] If checksums had been used, where the blocks of the "fake winner" transaction were tagged with a mutual checksum, the file system could have known better and not replayed the corrupt data onto the disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Journal checksumming has been added to ext4.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Filesystems going through the device mapper interface (including software RAID and LVM implementations) may not support barriers, and will issue a warning if that mount option is used.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There are also some disks that do not properly implement the write cache flushing extension necessary for barriers to work, which causes a similar warning.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] In these situations, where barriers are not supported or practical, reliable write ordering is possible by turning off the disk's write cache and using the `data=journal` mount option.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Turning off the disk's write cache may be required even when barriers are available.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Applications like databases expect a call to fsync() to flush pending writes to disk, and the barrier implementation doesn't always clear the drive's write cache in response to that call.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There is also a potential issue with the barrier implementation related to error handling during events, such as a drive failure.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] It is also known that sometimes some virtualization technologies do not properly forward fsync or flush commands to the underlying devices (files, volumes, disk) from a guest operating system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Similarly, some hard disks or controllers implement cache flushing incorrectly or not at all, but still advertise that it is supported, and do not return any error when it is used.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] There are so many ways to handle fsync and write cache handling incorrectly, it is safer to assume that cache flushing does not work unless it is explicitly tested, regardless of how reliable individual components are believed to be.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Both ext2 and ext3 use a 32‑bit signed integer to store timestamps, which will overflow on 18 January 2038. ext4 has been Y2K38‑safe since Linux kernel 4.3.6 and e2fsprogs 1.43, released in 2016.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] ext3 is considered stable but is no longer under active development.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] All major Linux distributions now use ext4 as their default filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] The separate `ext3` kernel module is no longer necessary; the `ext4` kernel driver handles ext2, ext3, and ext4 filesystems transparently.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] New installations should use ext4 or another modern filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Existing ext3 volumes can be upgraded to ext4 without reformatting, provided certain ext4 features are disabled at mount time.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] As of 2025, ext4 has become the default file system for major Linux distributions including Debian and Ubuntu.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] On June 28, 2006, Theodore Ts'o, the principal developer of ext3, announced an enhanced version, called ext4.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] On October 11, 2008, the patches that mark ext4 as stable code were merged in the Linux 2.6.28 source code repositories, marking the end of the development phase and recommending its adoption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext3] Btrfs also has "a number of the same design ideas that reiser3/4 had".
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ext4 was initially a series of backward-compatible extensions to ext3, many of them originally developed by Cluster File Systems for the Lustre file system between 2003 and 2006, meant to extend storage limits and add other performance improvements.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] However, other Linux kernel developers opposed accepting extensions to ext3 for stability reasons, and proposed to fork the source code of ext3, rename it as ext4, and perform all the development there, without affecting existing ext3 users.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This proposal was accepted, and on 28 June 2006, Theodore Ts'o, the ext3 maintainer, announced the new plan of development for ext4.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] A preliminary development version of ext4 was included in version 2.6.19 of the Linux kernel.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] On 11 October 2008, the patches that mark ext4 as stable code were merged in the Linux 2.6.28 source code repositories, denoting the end of the development phase and recommending ext4 adoption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Kernel 2.6.28, containing the ext4 filesystem, was finally released on 25 December 2008.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] On 15 January 2010, Google announced that it would upgrade its storage infrastructure from ext2 to ext4.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] On 14 December 2010, Google also announced it would use ext4, instead of YAFFS, on Android 2.3.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Its improvements over ext3 include a date range that ends in the year 2446 instead of 2038, a timestamp accuracy of a nanosecond instead of one second, and higher size limits.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ext4 is the default file system for many Linux distributions including Debian and Ubuntu.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] An extent is a range of contiguous physical blocks, improving large-file performance and reducing fragmentation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] of contiguous space with a 4 KiB block size.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This will slightly improve performance, because certain new features of the ext4 implementation can also be used with ext3 and ext2, such as the new block allocation algorithm, without affecting the on-disk format.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ext4 can pre-allocate on-disk space for a file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] To do this on most file systems, zeroes would be written to the file when created.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] , a new system call in the Linux kernel, can be used.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The allocated space would be guaranteed and likely contiguous.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This situation has applications for media streaming and databases.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] That is, ext4 delays block allocation until data is flushed to disk; in contrast, some file systems allocate blocks immediately, even when the data goes into a write cache.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] by effectively allocating larger amounts of data at a time.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ext4 does not limit the number of subdirectories in a single directory, except by the inherent size limit of the directory itself.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ) by default, which allows directories up to approximately 10–12 million entries to be stored in the 2-level HTree index and 2 GB directory size limit for 4 KiB block size, depending on the filename length.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] feature enabled a 3-level HTree and directory sizes over 2 GB, allowing approximately 6 billion entries in a single directory.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] in the journal to improve reliability, since the journal is one of the most used files of the disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This feature has a side benefit: it can safely avoid a disk I/O wait during journaling, improving performance slightly.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] with modifications within the implementation of compound transactions performed by the IRON file system (originally proposed by Sam Naghshineh in the RedHat summit).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Support for metadata checksums was added in Linux kernel version 3.5 released in 2012.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] checksums but some only store the lower 16 bits of the 32-bit checksum as there isn't enough previously reserved space to fit the whole 4 bytes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] In ext4 unallocated block groups and sections of the inode table are marked as such.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] to skip them entirely and greatly reduces the time it takes to check the file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] When ext3 appends to a file, it calls the block allocator, once for each block.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] However, ext4 uses delayed allocation, which allows it to buffer data and allocate groups of blocks.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The multiblock allocator can also be used when files are opened in O_DIRECT mode.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This feature does not affect the disk format.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] applications, the granularity of second-based timestamps becomes insufficient.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] ext4 also adds support for time-of-creation timestamps.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] These changes will require coordination of many projects.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Support for project quotas was added in Linux kernel 4.4 on 8 Jan 2016.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The project ID of a file is a 32-bit number stored on each file and is inherited by all files and subdirectories created beneath a parent directory with an assigned project ID.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This allows assigning quota limits to a particular subdirectory tree independent of file access permissions on the file, such as user and project quotas that are dependent on the UID and GID.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] While this is similar to a directory quota, the main difference is that the same project ID can be assigned to multiple top-level directories and is not strictly hierarchical.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Support for transparent encryption was added in Linux kernel 4.1 in June 2015.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The lazyinit feature allows cleaning of inode tables in background, speeding initialization when creating a new ext4 file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It is available since 2010 in Linux kernel version 2.6.37.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It ensures that file system metadata is correctly written and ordered on disk, even when write caches lose power.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This goes with a performance cost especially for applications that use fsync heavily or create and delete many small files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] For disks with a battery-backed write cache, disabling barriers (option 'barrier=0') may safely improve performance.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] In 2008, the principal developer of the ext3 and ext4 file systems, Theodore Ts'o, stated that although ext4 has improved features over ext3, it is not a major advancement, it is based on older technology.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Ts'o commented at the time that Btrfs may be the better direction because "it offers improvements in scalability, reliability, and ease of management".
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Btrfs also has "a number of the same design ideas that reiser3/4 had" that made it seem attractive at the time.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] However, Ts'o and many contributors from IBM, Google, SuSE, Huawei, and others, have continued to maintain and improve ext4 with new features such as file encryption, metadata checksums, and case insensitive filenames.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The ext4 file system does not honor the "secure deletion" file attribute, which is supposed to cause overwriting of files upon deletion.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] A patch to implement secure deletion was proposed in 2011, but did not solve the problem of sensitive data ending up in the file-system journal.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Because delayed allocation changes behavior that programmers relied on from ext3, the feature poses some additional risk of data loss in cases where the system crashes or loses power before all of the data has been written to disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Due to this, ext4 in kernel versions 2.6.30 and later automatically handles these cases as ext3 does.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The typical scenario in which this might occur is a program replacing the contents of a file without forcing a write to the disk with fsync.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Since the write can take some time, there is an opportunity of losing contents even with ext3, but usually very small.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] However, because ext4 can delay writing file data for a long time, this opportunity is much greater.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] If other processes access the file while it is being written, they see a corrupted version.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] If other processes have the file open and do not expect its contents to change, those processes may crash.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] One notable example is a shared library file which is mapped into running programs.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] A new temporary file ("file.new") is created, which initially contains the new contents.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Then the new file is renamed over the old one.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] standards – i.e. either the old file remains, or it is overwritten with the new one.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Using `fsync()` more often to reduce the risk for ext4 could lead to performance penalties on ext3 filesystems mounted with the `data=ordered` flag (the default on most Linux distributions).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Given that both file systems will be in use for some time, this complicates matters for end-user application developers.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] In response, ext4 in Linux kernels 2.6.30 and newer detect the occurrence of these common cases and force the files to be allocated immediately.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] For a small cost in performance, this provides semantics similar to ext3 ordered mode and increases the chance that either version of the file will survive the crash.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This new behavior is enabled by default, but can be disabled with the "noauto_da_alloc" mount option.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The new patches have become part of the mainline kernel 2.6.30, but various distributions chose to backport them to 2.6.28 or 2.6.29.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] These patches don't completely prevent potential data loss or help at all with new files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The only way to be safe is to write and use software that does `fsync()` when it needs to.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Performance problems can be minimized by limiting crucial disk writes that need `fsync()` to occur less frequently.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Linux kernel Virtual File System is a subsystem or layer inside of the Linux kernel.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It is the result of an attempt to integrate multiple file systems into an orderly single structure.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The key idea, which dates back to the pioneering work done by Sun Microsystems employees in 1986, is to abstract out that part of the file system that is common to all file systems and put that code in a separate layer that calls the underlying concrete file systems to actually manage the data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] All system calls related to files (or pseudo files) are directed to the Linux kernel Virtual File System for initial processing.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] These calls, coming from user processes, are the standard POSIX calls, such as `open`, `read`, `write`, `lseek`, etc.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Although designed for and primarily used with Linux, an ext4 file system can be accessed via other operating systems via interoperability tools.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Windows provides access via its Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) technology.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Specifically, the second major version, WSL 2, is the first version with ext4 support.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It was first released in Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 20211.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] WSL 2 requires Windows 10 version 1903 or higher, with build 18362 or higher, for x64 systems, and version 2004 or higher, with build 19041 or higher, for ARM64 systems.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Paragon Software offers commercial products that provide full read/write access for ext2/3/4 – *Linux File Systems for Windows* and *extFS for Mac*.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The free software *ext4fuse* provides limited (read-only) support.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The ext4 filesystem divides the partition it resides into smaller chunks called blocks (a group of sectors, usually between 1 KiB and 64 KiB).
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] By default, the block size is the same as the page size (4 KiB), but it can be configured with mkfs during filesystem creation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Blocks are grouped into larger chunks called block groups.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This is the heart of the filesystem; it resides in only one block of the disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It is usually the first item in a block group, except for group 0, where the first few bytes are reserved for the boot sector.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The Superblock is vital for the filesystem – as such, backup copies are written across partitions at filesystem creation time, so it can be recovered in case of corruption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] GDT stores block group descriptors of each block group on the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It resides on more than one block on disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] This structure is also vital for the filesystem; as such, redundant backups are stored across the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The Block bitmap tracks the block usage status of all blocks of a block group.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Each bit in the bitmap represents a block.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] If a block is in use, its corresponding bit will be set; otherwise, it will be unset.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The location of the block bitmap is not fixed, so its position is stored in respective block group descriptors.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Similar to the Block bitmap, the Inode bitmap's location is also not fixed; therefore, the group descriptor points to the location of the Inode bitmap.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] The Inode bitmap tracks usage of inodes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Each bit in the bitmap represents an inode.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] If an inode is in use then its corresponding bit in Inode bitmap will be set; otherwise, it will be unset.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Each block group is represented by its block group descriptor.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] It has vital information for the block group like free inodes, free blocks and the location of inode bitmap, block bitmap and the inode table of that particular block group.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] In flex_bg, several block groups are grouped into one logical block group.
[src:ext4-filesystem/ext4] Block bitmap and inode bitmap of first block group are expanded to include the bitmap and the inode table of other block groups.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] In computing, an **extent** is a contiguous area of storage reserved for a file in a file system, represented as a range of block numbers, or tracks on count key data devices.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] A file can consist of zero or more extents; one file fragment requires one extent.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] The direct benefit is in storing each range compactly as two numbers, instead of canonically storing every block number in the range.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] Also, extent allocation results in less file fragmentation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] Extent-based file systems can also eliminate most of the metadata overhead of large files that would traditionally be taken up by the block-allocation tree.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] But because the savings are small compared to the amount of stored data (for all file sizes in general) but make up a large portion of the metadata (for large files), the overall benefits in storage efficiency and performance are slight.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] In order to resist fragmentation, several extent-based file systems do allocate-on-flush.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] Many modern fault-tolerant file systems also do copy-on-write, although that increases fragmentation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] As a similar design, the CP/M file system uses extents as well, but those do not correspond to the definition given above.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] CP/M's extents appear contiguously as a single block in the combined directory/allocation table, and they do not necessarily correspond to a contiguous data area on disk.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] IBM OS/360 and successors allocate files in multiples of disk tracks or cylinders.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] Files could originally have up to 16 extents, but this restriction has since been lifted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] The initial allocation size, and the size of additional extents to be allocated if required, are specified by the user via Job Control Language.
[src:ext4-filesystem/extent-file-systems] The system attempts to allocate the initial size as a contiguous area, although this may be split if contiguous space is not available.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] An **inode** (index node) is a data structure in a Unix-style file system that describes a file-system object such as a file or a directory.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Each inode stores the attributes and disk block locations of the object's data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] File-system object attributes may include metadata (times of last change, access, modification), as well as owner and permission data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A directory is a list of inodes with their assigned names.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The list includes an entry for itself, its parent, and each of its children.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] There has been uncertainty on the Linux kernel mailing list about the reason for the "i" in "inode".
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A 1978 paper by Ritchie and Ken Thompson bolsters the notion of "index" being the etymological origin of inodes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Bach wrote that the word *inode* "is a contraction of the term index node and is commonly used in literature on the UNIX system".
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A file system relies on data structures *about* the files, as opposed to the contents of those files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The former are called *metadata*—data that describes data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Each file is associated with an *inode*, which is identified by an integer, often referred to as an *i-number* or *inode number*.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Inodes store information about files and directories (folders), such as file ownership, access mode (read, write, execute permissions), and file type.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The data may be called stat data, in reference to the `stat` system call that provides the data to programs.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The inode number indexes a table of inodes on the file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] From the inode number, the kernel's file system driver can access the inode contents, including the location of the file, thereby allowing access to the file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A file's inode number can be found using the `ls -i` command, which prints the inode number in the first column of its output.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] On many older file systems, inodes are stored in one or more fixed-size areas that are set up at file system creation time, so the maximum number of inodes is fixed at file system creation, limiting the maximum number of files the file system can hold.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A typical allocation heuristic for inodes in a file system is one inode for every 2K bytes contained in the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Some Unix-style file systems such as JFS, XFS, ZFS, OpenZFS, ReiserFS, btrfs, and APFS omit a fixed-size inode table, but must store equivalent data in order to provide equivalent capabilities.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Common alternatives to the fixed-size table include B-trees and the derived B+ trees.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The operating system kernel's in-memory representation of this data is called `struct inode` in Linux.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Systems derived from BSD use the term `vnode` (the "v" refers to the kernel's virtual file system layer).
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The POSIX standard mandates file-system behavior that is strongly influenced by traditional UNIX file systems.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] An inode is denoted by the phrase "file serial number", defined as a *per-file system* unique identifier for a file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] That file serial number, together with the device ID of the device containing the file, uniquely identify the file within the whole system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] If multiple names hard link to the same inode then the names are equivalent; i.e., the first to be created has no special status.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This is unlike symbolic links, which depend on the original name, not the inode (number).
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] An inode without links represents a file with no remaining directory entries or paths leading to it in the filesystem.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] A file that has been deleted or lacks directory entries pointing to it is termed an 'unlinked' file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Such files are removed from the filesystem, freeing the occupied disk space for reuse.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] An inode without links remains in the filesystem until the resources (disk space and blocks) freed by the unlinked file are deallocated or the file system is modified.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Although an unlinked file becomes invisible in the filesystem, its deletion is deferred until all processes with access to the file have finished using it, including executable files which are implicitly held open by the processes executing them.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] It is typically not possible to map from an open file to the filename that was used to open it.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] When a program opens a file, the operating system converts the filename to an inode number and then discards the filename.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] As a result, functions like getcwd() and getwd() which retrieve the current working directory of the process, cannot directly access the filename.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Beginning with the current directory, these functions search up to its parent directory, then to the parent's parent, and so on, until reaching the root directory.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] At each level, the function looks for a directory entry whose inode matches that of the directory it just moved up from.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Because the child directory's inode still exists as an entry in its parent directory, it allows the function to reconstruct the absolute path of the current working directory.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Some operating systems maintain extra information to make this operation run faster.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] For example, in the Linux VFS, directory entry cache, also known as dentry or dcache, are cache entries used by the kernel to speed up filesystem operations by storing information about directory links in RAM.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Historically, it was possible to hard link directories.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This made the directory structure an arbitrary directed graph contrary to a directed acyclic graph.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] It was even possible for a directory to be its own parent.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Modern systems generally prohibit this confusing state, except that the parent of *root* is still defined as root.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The most notable exception to this prohibition is found in Mac OS X (versions 10.5 and higher) which allows hard links of directories to be created on HFS+ file systems by the superuser.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] When a file is relocated to a different directory on the same file system, or when a disk defragmentation alters its physical location, the file's inode number remains unchanged.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This unique characteristic permits the file to be moved or renamed even during read or write operations, thereby ensuring continuous access without disruptions.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] In these file systems, moving or renaming a file might lead to more significant changes in the data structure representing the file, and the system does not keep a separate, central record of the file's data block locations and metadata as inodes do in Unix-like systems.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] inode file systems allow a running process to continue accessing a library file even as another process is replacing that same file.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This operation should be performed atomically, meaning it should appear as a single operation that is either entirely completed or not done at all, with no intermediate state visible to other processes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] During the replacement, a new inode is created for the new library file, establishing an entirely new mapping.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Subsequently, future access requests for that library will retrieve the newly installed version.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] When the operating system is replacing the file (and creating a new inode), it places a lock on the inode and possibly the containing directory.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This prevents other processes from reading or writing to the file (inode) during the update operation, thereby avoiding data inconsistency or corruption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Once the update operation is complete, the lock is released.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Any subsequent access to the file (via the inode) by any processes will now point to the new version of the library.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Thus, making it possible to perform updates even when the library is in use by another process.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] One significant advantage of this mechanism is that it eliminates the need for a system reboot to replace libraries currently in use.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Consequently, systems can update or upgrade software libraries seamlessly without interrupting running processes or operations.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] When a file system is created, some file systems allocate a fixed number of inodes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This means that it is possible to run out of inodes on a file system, even if there is free space remaining in the file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This situation often arises in use cases where there are many small files, such as on a server storing email messages, because each file, no matter how small, requires its own inode.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Other file systems avoid this limitation by using dynamic inode allocation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Dynamic inode allocation allows a file system to create more inodes as needed instead of relying on a fixed number created at the time of file system creation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This can "grow" the file system by increasing the number of inodes available for new files and directories, thus avoiding the problem of running out of inodes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] It can make sense to store very small files in the inode itself to save both space (no data block needed) and lookup time (no further disk access needed).
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] This file system feature is called inlining.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] The strict separation of inode and file data thus can no longer be assumed when using modern file systems.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] If the data of a file fits in the space allocated for pointers to the data, this space can conveniently be used.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] For example, ext2 and its successors store the data of symlinks (typically file names) in this way if the data is no more than 60 bytes ("fast symbolic links").
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Ext4 has a file system option called `inline_data` that allows ext4 to perform inlining if enabled during file system creation.
[src:ext4-filesystem/inode] Because an inode's size is limited, this only works for very small files.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A **journaling file system** is a file system that keeps track of changes not yet committed to the file system's main part by recording the goal of such changes in a data structure known as a "journal", which is usually a circular log.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In the event of a system crash or power failure, such file systems can be brought back online more quickly with a lower likelihood of becoming corrupted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Depending on the actual implementation, a journaling file system may only keep track of stored metadata, resulting in improved performance at the expense of increased possibility for data corruption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Alternatively, a journaling file system may track both stored data and related metadata, while some implementations allow selectable behavior in this regard.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In 1990 IBM introduced JFS in AIX 3.1 as one of the first UNIX commercial filesystems that implemented journaling.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The next year the idea was popularized in a widely cited paper on log-structured file systems.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This was subsequently implemented in Microsoft's Windows NT's NTFS filesystem in 1993, in Apple's HFS Plus filesystem in 1998, and in Linux's ext3 filesystem in 2001.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Updating file systems to reflect changes to files and directories usually requires many separate write operations.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This makes it possible for an interruption (like a power failure or system crash) between writes to leave data structures in an invalid intermediate state.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Releasing the inode to the pool of free inodes.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Returning all disk blocks to the pool of free disk blocks.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If a crash occurs after step 1 and before step 2, there will be an orphaned inode and hence a storage leak; if a crash occurs between steps 2 and 3, then the blocks previously used by the file cannot be used for new files, effectively decreasing the storage capacity of the file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Re-arranging the steps does not help, either.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If step 3 preceded step 1, a crash between them could allow the file's blocks to be reused for a new file, meaning the partially deleted file would contain part of the contents of another file, and modifications to either file would show up in both.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] On the other hand, if step 2 preceded step 1, a crash between them would cause the file to be inaccessible, despite appearing to exist.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Detecting and recovering from such inconsistencies normally requires a complete walk of its data structures, for example by a tool such as fsck (the file system checker).
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This must typically be done before the file system is next mounted for read-write access.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If the file system is large and if there is relatively little I/O bandwidth, this can take a long time and result in longer downtimes if it blocks the rest of the system from coming back online.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To prevent this, a journaled file system allocates a special area—the journal—in which it records the changes it will make ahead of time.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] After a crash, recovery simply involves reading the journal from the file system and replaying changes from this journal until the file system is consistent again.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The changes are thus said to be atomic (not divisible) in that they either succeed (succeeded originally or are replayed completely during recovery), or are not replayed at all (are skipped because they had not yet been completely written to the journal before the crash occurred).
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some file systems allow the journal to grow, shrink and be re-allocated just as a regular file, while others put the journal in a contiguous area or a hidden file that is guaranteed not to move or change size while the file system is mounted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some file systems may also allow *external journals* on a separate device, such as a solid-state drive or battery-backed non-volatile RAM.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Changes to the journal may themselves be journaled for additional redundancy, or the journal may be distributed across multiple physical volumes to protect against device failure.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The internal format of the journal must guard against crashes while the journal itself is being written to.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Many journal implementations (such as the JBD2 layer in ext4) bracket every change logged with a checksum, on the understanding that a crash would leave a partially written change with a missing (or mismatched) checksum that can simply be ignored when replaying the journal at next remount.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A *physical journal* logs an advance copy of every block that will later be written to the main file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If there is a crash when the main file system is being written to, the write can simply be replayed to completion when the file system is next mounted.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If there is a crash when the write is being logged to the journal, the partial write will have a missing or mismatched checksum and can be ignored at next mount.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Physical journals impose a significant performance penalty because every changed block must be committed *twice* to storage, but may be acceptable when absolute fault protection is required.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A *logical journal* stores only changes to file metadata in the journal, and trades fault tolerance for substantially better write performance.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] A file system with a logical journal still recovers quickly after a crash, but may allow unjournaled file data and journaled metadata to fall out of sync with each other, causing data corruption.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The free space map, to mark out an allocation of space for the to-be-appended data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The newly allocated space, to actually write the appended data.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In a metadata-only journal, step 3 would not be logged.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] If step 3 was not done, but steps 1 and 2 are replayed during recovery, the file will be appended with garbage.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] The write cache in most operating systems sorts its writes (using the elevator algorithm or some similar scheme) to maximize throughput.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To avoid an out-of-order write hazard with a metadata-only journal, writes for file data must be sorted so that they are committed to storage before their associated metadata.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This can be tricky to implement because it requires coordination within the operating system kernel between the file system driver and write cache.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] An out-of-order write hazard can also occur if a device cannot write blocks immediately to its underlying storage, that is, it cannot flush its write-cache to disk due to deferred write being enabled.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To complicate matters, many mass storage devices have their own write caches, in which they may aggressively reorder writes for better performance.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] Some UFS implementations avoid journaling and instead implement soft updates: they order their writes in such a way that the on-disk file system is never inconsistent, or that the only inconsistency that can be created in the event of a crash is a storage leak.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] To recover from these leaks, the free space map is reconciled against a full walk of the file system at next mount.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This garbage collection is usually done in the background.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] In log-structured file systems, the write-twice penalty does not apply because the journal itself *is* the file system: it occupies the entire storage device and is structured so that it can be traversed as would a normal file system.
[src:ext4-filesystem/journaling-file-system] This has the same correctness-preserving properties as a journal, without the write-twice overhead.
